    \section{Solving Overdetermined
Systems}\label{solving-overdetermined-systems}

\subsection{Approach}\label{approach}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Normalize data
\item
  Cluster to best cluster
\item
  Find solution to each system of three equations from clusters, and
  average the solutions
\item
  Find solution algebraically
\item
  Compare solutions and see how they differ
\item
  Use an approach where if the system is unsolvable, take the average
  plane
\end{itemize}

    \subsection{Creating Data}\label{creating-data}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{readcsv}: Takes in a csv file and imports that data

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: a filename (e.g. "testdata.csv")
  \item
    Output: a matrix where each row represents an equation
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{makedataNum}: Takes in a number of clusters and generates a
  random number of equations, with the equations clustered in the
  specified number of groups. Equations are stored in a matrix.

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: a natural number with the number of clusters
  \item
    Output: a matrix where each row represents an equation
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{makedataRandom}: Takes in a number of equations, and generates
  that number of equations randomly. Equations are stored in a matrix.

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: a natural number with the number of equations
  \item
    Output: a matrix where each row represents an equation
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

    \subsection{Normalizing Data}\label{normalizing-data}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist

  \texttt{normalize}: Use the L2 norm to normalize the data to make
  every equation in a matrix have a unit normal

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: matrix with rows as equations
  \item
    Output: matrix with each row having equations with unit norms
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{normalizeL1}: Use the L1 norm to normalize the data to make
  every equation in a matrix have a unit normal

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: matrix with rows as equations
  \item
    Output: matrix with each row having equations with unit norms
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

    \subsection{Clustering Data Points}\label{clustering-data-points}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Overall approach: Use k-means clustering
\item
  To find the actual optimal cluster of k, plot the sum squared errors
  with each k, and find an "elbow" in the graph. The location of that
  elbow indicates what k we should cluster with
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Functions}\label{functions}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{bestkcluster}: Plots a graph of the sum squared errors
  clustering with different values of k

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: a matrix of equations \texttt{matrix}, the maximum number of
    clusters to test \texttt{maxclusters}
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{kcluster}: Cluster the equations of the system into a
  specified number of clusters

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: matrix of equations \texttt{matrix}, the number of clusters
    \texttt{k}
  \item
    Output: matrix of equations representing the center of the clusters
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

    \subsection{Finding Solutions}\label{finding-solutions}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{algsolution}: Algebraically finds the solution to the system
  of equations

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: matrix with rows of the form ax + by + cz = d
  \item
    Output: Solution as (x, y, z)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{solution}: Solves the system of equations when the system is
  not overdetermined

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: matrix with rows of the form ax + by + cz = d, and number of
    rows are one less then the number of columns
  \item
    Output: Solution as (x, y, z)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{avgsolution}: Take all subsets of an overdetermined system
  that together gives a solution, then averages among the solutions

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Input: matrix with rows of the form ax + by + cz = d
  \item
    Output: Solution as (x, y, z)
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
